## JavaScript Debounce Function

A debounce function delays executing a function until after a specified wait time has elapsed since the last time it was called.

```javascript
// Debounce function
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timer;
  return function (...args) {
    clearTimeout(timer);
    timer = setTimeout(() => fn.apply(this, args), delay);
  };
}

// --- Example Usage ---

// Simulates an API call triggered by a search input
function fetchSearchResults(query) {
  console.log(`Fetching results for: "${query}"`);
}

const debouncedSearch = debounce(fetchSearchResults, 300);

// Simulating rapid keystrokes — only the last call fires after 300ms
debouncedSearch("j");
debouncedSearch("ja");
debouncedSearch("jav");
debouncedSearch("java"); // ✅ Only this call executes after 300ms
```

### How it works

| Step | What happens |
|------|-------------|
| 1 | A new call clears the existing timer with `clearTimeout` |
| 2 | A fresh `setTimeout` is started |
| 3 | If no new call arrives within `delay` ms, the function executes |
| 4 | If a new call arrives, the timer resets and the cycle repeats |

**Common use cases:** search inputs, window resize handlers, and form auto-save.
